{
  "Glaciers form when:": "",
  "Accumulated snow compacts into ice over many years and begins to move under its own weight": "",
  "A single heavy snowfall compresses into ice overnight": "",
  "Seawater freezes along coastal areas": "",
  "Rivers freeze solid during winter": "",
  "Glaciers form from snow that accumulates year after year, with lower layers compressing into firn and then dense glacial ice that eventually flows under its own gravitational pressure.": "",
  "What shape of valley is created by glacial erosion?": "",
  "A flat-bottomed rift valley": "",
  "A wide U-shaped valley": "",
  "A narrow V-shaped valley": "",
  "A deep vertical canyon": "",
  "Glaciers carve wide, flat-bottomed U-shaped valleys as their immense mass grinds away both the valley floor and walls, producing a much broader profile than the V-shaped valleys cut by rivers.": "",
  "Milankovitch cycles influence ice ages through changes in:": "",
  "The Moon's distance from Earth": "",
  "Volcanic eruption frequency": "",
  "Earth's orbital shape, axial tilt, and wobble": "",
  "The Sun's energy output": "",
  "Milankovitch cycles are periodic variations in Earth's eccentricity, axial tilt (obliquity), and precession that alter how much solar energy different latitudes receive, triggering glacial and interglacial periods over tens of thousands of years.": "",
  "The most recent ice age ended approximately:": "",
  "1 million years ago": "",
  "11,700 years ago": "",
  "1,000 years ago": "",
  "100,000 years ago": "",
  "The last glacial period ended about 11,700 years ago, marking the beginning of the current Holocene interglacial epoch in which human civilization developed.": "",
  "How do fjords form?": "",
  "Volcanic eruptions create coastal channels": "",
  "Rivers flood narrow valleys near the coast": "",
  "Earthquakes split coastal rock apart": "",
  "Glacially carved valleys are flooded by rising sea levels": "",
  "Fjords are deep, narrow coastal inlets that formed when glaciers carved valleys below sea level, and as the ice retreated and sea levels rose, seawater flooded these over-deepened valleys.": "",
  "What happens to sea level when glaciers melt?": "",
  "Sea level stays the same because the water was already part of the ocean": "",
  "Sea level rises as meltwater returns to the oceans": "",
  "Sea level drops because glacial meltwater evaporates quickly": "",
  "Sea level falls because water is absorbed by the ground": "",
  "When glaciers melt, water that was locked up on land as ice flows back into the oceans, increasing their volume and causing sea levels to rise, threatening low-lying coastal areas worldwide.": "",
  "Plucking is a glacial erosion process where:": "",
  "Wind removes loose sediment from the glacier surface": "",
  "Meltwater dissolves limestone beneath the glacier": "",
  "Tree roots crack rocks along the glacier margin": "",
  "Moving ice freezes onto bedrock and pulls rock fragments away as it advances": "",
  "As a glacier moves, meltwater seeps into cracks in the bedrock and refreezes, bonding to the ice above, so when the glacier advances, it plucks these rock fragments away from the surface.": "",
  "The Great Lakes were formed by:": "",
  "River erosion carving deep channels": "",
  "Glacial erosion and deposition during the last ice age": "",
  "Tectonic rifting splitting the continent apart": "",
  "Volcanic activity creating large craters": "",
  "The Great Lakes were carved by massive continental glaciers during the last ice age, which scoured out deep basins in the bedrock, and as the glaciers retreated, meltwater filled these basins to create the lakes.": "",
  "During the peak of the last ice age about 20,000 years ago, approximately what percentage of Earth's land was covered by ice?": "",
  "5%": "",
  "50%": "",
  "90%": "",
  "30%": "",
  "At the peak of the last glacial maximum, about 30% of Earth's land surface was covered by ice sheets and glaciers, compared to approximately 10% today, with massive ice sheets covering much of North America and Europe.": "",
  "Current climate change is causing glaciers worldwide to:": "",
  "Retreat at accelerating rates": "",
  "Stay approximately the same size": "",
  "Grow larger each year": "",
  "Move sideways rather than forward or backward": "",
  "Rising global temperatures are causing the vast majority of glaciers worldwide to lose mass and retreat at accelerating rates, as documented by satellite monitoring and ground measurements since the 1800s.": "",
  "What is a glacial erratic?": "",
  "A large boulder deposited far from its source by a retreating glacier": "",
  "A deep scratch on bedrock caused by glacial abrasion": "",
  "A lake that forms in a glacially carved depression": "",
  "A type of moraine found at the terminus of a glacier": "",
  "A glacial erratic is a boulder transported by glacial ice far from its original location and deposited when the ice melts, often appearing completely different from the local bedrock and looking conspicuously out of place.": "",
  "What is a moraine?": "",
  "A frozen lake on the surface of a glacier": "",
  "A ridge or mound of unsorted sediment deposited by a glacier, marking its former extent": "",
  "A fast-flowing river of glacial meltwater": "",
  "A deep crevasse in the surface of a glacier": "",
  "A moraine is an accumulation of unsorted glacial debris (till) deposited in ridges along the sides, center, or terminus of a glacier, serving as evidence of the glacier's former size and extent.": "",
  "What are glacial striations?": "",
  "Scratches carved into bedrock by rocks embedded in the base of a moving glacier": "",
  "Patterns of light and dark ice caused by seasonal snowfall": "",
  "Layers of ice visible in the cross-section of a glacier": "",
  "Cracks that form on the surface of a glacier from stress": "",
  "Glacial striations are parallel scratches and grooves carved into bedrock by rocks and debris frozen into the bottom of a moving glacier, providing evidence of the glacier's direction of movement.": "",
  "What is firn?": "",
  "Volcanic rock found beneath glaciers": "",
  "Meltwater that flows beneath a glacier": "",
  "Compacted, granular snow that is transitional between fresh snow and glacial ice": "",
  "A type of glacier that forms only in tropical mountains": "",
  "Firn is partially compacted granular snow that has survived at least one summer melt season, representing an intermediate stage between freshly fallen snow and the dense, crystal-clear glacial ice that forms under continued compression.": "",
  "What is a continental glacier?": "",
  "A small glacier confined to a single mountain valley": "",
  "A frozen river that forms in arctic climates": "",
  "A massive ice sheet that covers an enormous area of a continent, such as those in Antarctica and Greenland": "",
  "Sea ice that extends from a continent's coastline": "",
  "Continental glaciers, or ice sheets, are vast masses of ice that spread over large portions of a continent, reaching thicknesses of several kilometers, with the Antarctic and Greenland ice sheets being the two that exist today.": "",
  "What does 'glacial retreat' mean?": "",
  "The glacier's front edge recedes because melting exceeds new ice formation": "",
  "The glacier physically moves backward uphill": "",
  "The glacier splits into multiple smaller glaciers": "",
  "The glacier sinks into the ground": "",
  "Glacial retreat does not mean the ice moves backward; rather, the terminus position recedes because the glacier is melting at its front faster than new ice advances from the accumulation zone, causing a net loss of ice.": "",
  "What is an alpine glacier?": "",
  "Sea ice that forms in polar oceans": "",
  "A permanently frozen lake at high elevation": "",
  "A glacier that covers an entire continent": "",
  "A glacier confined to a mountain valley that flows downhill under its own weight": "",
  "Alpine glaciers, also called valley glaciers, form in mountain valleys above the snowline and flow downhill like slow rivers of ice, carving distinctive features like cirques, aretes, and U-shaped valleys.": "",
  "What is a cirque?": "",
  "A flat plain of glacial outwash sediment": "",
  "A ridge of glacial debris along the side of a valley": "",
  "A bowl-shaped depression carved into a mountainside at the head of a glacier": "",
  "A deep crack in the surface of a glacier": "",
  "A cirque is an amphitheater-shaped hollow carved into a mountainside by the erosive action of a glacier at its source, and after the glacier melts, the cirque may contain a small lake called a tarn.": "",
  "What does the term 'glacial till' mean?": "",
  "Wind-blown dust that accumulates near glacier margins": "",
  "Sorted layers of sand and gravel deposited by meltwater streams": "",
  "Unsorted sediment of mixed sizes deposited directly by glacial ice as it melts": "",
  "Volcanic ash that settles on the surface of a glacier": "",
  "Glacial till is an unsorted mixture of sediment ranging from fine clay to massive boulders that is deposited directly by glacial ice, unlike outwash deposits which are sorted by meltwater into layers by particle size.": "",
  "What does 'Milankovitch cycles' mean?": "",
  "The regular pattern of ocean current reversals": "",
  "Periodic changes in Earth's orbital eccentricity, axial tilt, and precession that affect solar energy distribution and drive ice age cycles": "",
  "The annual freeze-thaw cycle of seasonal ice": "",
  "Cycles of volcanic eruptions that trigger climate change": "",
  "Milankovitch cycles are three predictable astronomical variations in Earth's orbit and orientation that operate on time scales of roughly 26,000 to 100,000 years, altering the distribution of solar energy and pacing the onset of glacial and interglacial periods.": "",
  "A geologist hiking in Central Park, New York City, discovers large scratches running north-to-south on exposed bedrock and a massive boulder made of granite sitting on top of limestone bedrock. The granite does not match any local rock formations. What glacial evidence is the geologist observing?": "",
  "Evidence of an ancient river that flowed through Manhattan": "",
  "Damage from an ancient earthquake that cracked the bedrock": "",
  "Glacial striations showing ice flow direction and a glacial erratic transported from a distant source": "",
  "Evidence that the boulder was placed there by early human settlers": "",
  "The parallel scratches are glacial striations carved by rocks embedded in the base of a moving ice sheet, indicating the direction of glacial flow, and the out-of-place granite boulder is a glacial erratic transported far from its source.": "",
  "Scientists studying ice cores from Antarctica find that atmospheric CO2 levels and temperature have risen and fallen together in a regular pattern over the past 800,000 years. These cycles correspond to known Milankovitch cycle timings. What does this evidence suggest about the relationship between orbital changes and climate?": "",
  "Milankovitch cycles have no effect on climate and the correlation is coincidental": "",
  "Changes in Earth's orbital parameters trigger warming and cooling, which are then amplified by greenhouse gas feedbacks": "",
  "CO2 directly controls Earth's orbital parameters": "",
  "Ice ages are caused solely by volcanic eruptions, not orbital changes": "",
  "Ice core data shows that Milankovitch cycles initiate temperature changes by altering solar energy distribution, which then trigger feedbacks including changes in CO2 and other greenhouse gases that amplify the warming or cooling.": "",
  "A coastal city in Bangladesh is already experiencing frequent flooding at high tide, and scientists project that melting of the Greenland and Antarctic ice sheets will raise sea levels by 1 to 2 meters by 2100. What is the primary concern for this city?": "",
  "Glaciers will advance and physically crush the city": "",
  "Rising sea levels from melting glacial ice will permanently inundate low-lying areas, displacing millions of people": "",
  "Ice chunks from glaciers will float to Bangladesh and block the harbor": "",
  "The melting ice will make the ocean water too cold for fishing": "",
  "When ice sheets on land melt, the meltwater flows into the oceans and raises sea level, threatening low-lying coastal cities like those in Bangladesh with permanent flooding, saltwater intrusion, and displacement of populations.": "",
  "Tourists visiting Norway are amazed by the deep, narrow waterways with steep cliffs that extend far inland from the coast. A tour guide explains these were carved during the last ice age. What geological process created these spectacular features?": "",
  "Tectonic faulting split the coastline into narrow channels": "",
  "Volcanic eruptions created long, narrow craters that filled with seawater": "",
  "Glaciers carved deep valleys below sea level, and rising seas flooded them when the ice retreated, creating fjords": "",
  "Rivers eroded narrow channels that were later widened by waves": "",
  "Norway's fjords were carved by glaciers that eroded deep valleys well below sea level during the ice ages, and when the glaciers melted and sea levels rose, seawater flooded these over-deepened valleys to create the dramatic fjord landscapes.": "",
  "A farmer in Wisconsin finds that his soil is a mixture of clay, sand, gravel, and boulders all jumbled together with no sorting by size. A geologist tells him this soil composition is typical of the area. What is the origin of this mixed-up soil?": "",
  "The soil was formed from glacial till deposited by ice sheets during the last ice age": "",
  "Volcanic eruptions scattered debris across the landscape": "",
  "River flooding deposited sorted layers that were later mixed by plowing": "",
  "Wind deposited different-sized particles at different times": "",
  "Much of Wisconsin's soil is derived from glacial till, the unsorted mixture of all sediment sizes deposited directly by the melting ice sheet, which unlike water or wind deposits does not sort particles by size.": "",
  "A mountaineering team climbing in the Swiss Alps observes a sharp, knife-like ridge separating two bowl-shaped depressions on either side of the mountain. What glacial features are they observing?": "",
  "A moraine between two river valleys": "",
  "A volcanic ridge with craters on both sides": "",
  "An arete formed between two cirques that were carved by glaciers on opposite sides of the ridge": "",
  "A fault line with collapsed terrain on each side": "",
  "An arete is a narrow, knife-edged ridge that forms when two glaciers erode cirques on opposite sides of a mountain, gradually narrowing the ridge between them into a dramatic, jagged crest.": "",
  "Engineers building a road through a valley in Montana discover that the valley floor has a flat bottom with steep, nearly vertical walls, unlike the typical V-shaped river valleys nearby. The valley also contains several small lakes and scattered large boulders. What can they conclude about the valley's history?": "",
  "The valley was formed by underground rivers dissolving the limestone bedrock": "",
  "The valley was created by wind erosion during a very dry climate period": "",
  "The valley was created by a massive earthquake splitting the ground apart": "",
  "The valley was carved by a glacier, as evidenced by its U-shape, scattered erratics, and small lakes in glacially scoured depressions": "",
  "The U-shaped profile, scattered large boulders (erratics), and small lakes (tarns) in scoured depressions are all hallmark features of glacial erosion, clearly distinguishing this valley from the V-shaped valleys carved by nearby rivers.": "",
  "A climate scientist presents data showing that global glacial ice volume has been decreasing at an accelerating rate since the 1990s. Satellite measurements show that the Greenland ice sheet alone lost approximately 280 billion tons of ice per year from 2002 to 2020. A student asks what the practical consequence of this ice loss is. What is the most accurate answer?": "",
  "The melting ice is cooling the oceans, which will eventually stop the melting": "",
  "The ice loss is being replaced by new snowfall at the same rate": "",
  "The melting ice contributes to rising sea levels, threatening coastal communities, while also reducing freshwater reserves stored in glaciers": "",
  "The lost ice has no measurable effect on global conditions": "",
  "Melting glacial ice on land directly raises sea levels as meltwater enters the oceans, and the loss of glaciers also threatens freshwater supplies for billions of people who depend on glacial meltwater for drinking water and agriculture.": "",
  "During a field trip to the Great Lakes region, students find parallel grooves scratched into exposed limestone bedrock all pointing in a north-to-south direction. Their teacher explains this is evidence of past glaciation. How do these grooves help scientists understand ice age glaciers?": "",
  "The grooves show where meltwater rivers flowed during the ice age": "",
  "The grooves were made by ancient humans carving paths through the rock": "",
  "The scratches indicate where earthquakes fractured the bedrock during the ice age": "",
  "The striations reveal the direction the glacier was moving, showing that ice flowed from north to south across this area": "",
  "Glacial striations are scratched into bedrock by rocks frozen into the base of a glacier, and their orientation directly indicates the direction of ice flow, allowing scientists to reconstruct the movement patterns of ancient ice sheets.": "",
  "A community in Peru relies on meltwater from a nearby glacier for their drinking water and agricultural irrigation during the dry season. Over the past 30 years, they have noticed the glacier shrinking significantly. Scientists predict the glacier will disappear completely within 20 years. What long-term water supply crisis does this community face?": "",
  "Once the glacier disappears, the community will lose its reliable dry-season water source since there will be no stored ice to melt gradually during months without rain": "",
  "The glacier melting will create a permanent river that replaces the glacier": "",
  "New glaciers will form to replace the one that melted": "",
  "They will have too much water as the entire glacier melts at once": "",
  "Glaciers act as natural water storage systems, accumulating snow in the wet season and releasing meltwater during dry periods, so when the glacier disappears, the community loses this crucial buffer and faces severe water shortages during the dry season.": ""
}